{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01SL9vXMuMRnJhsUfgP5EmPx","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"layout\": \"deck_close\",\n3\t  \"content\": {\n4\t    \"unified_point\": \"A single envelope catastrophe \\u2014 lipid A loss \\u2014 triggers five partially independent adaptive layers (Fur-released transport, ChvI two-phase signaling, constitutive sphingolipid substitution, peptidoglycan remodeling, and cross-species structural unavailability) that together explain how and why Caulobacter alone tolerates the deletion.\",\n5\t    \"key_takeaways\": [\n6\t      \"Fur-released transport relief is real and fitness-bearing in Path A transporters, but the SspB-buffered respiratory arm shows no fitness signal.\",\n7\t      \"ChvI drives a two-phase program \\u2014 regulators early, envelope-structural genes late \\u2014 but the membrane substitute itself is set elsewhere.\",\n8\t      \"A constitutive anionic-sphingolipid pool substitutes for lipid A, transported by maintained Lpt machinery \\u2014 not an inducible emergency response.\",\n9\t      \"Peptidoglycan synthesis is broadly downshifted with targeted Pal-Tol induction \\u2014 a coordinated remodel that raises why only Caulobacter survives it.\",\n10\t      \"The sphingolipid pathway and ChvG-ChvI are taxonomically restricted; comparator species lack the route entirely and use alternative strategies instead.\"\n11\t    ],\n12\t    \"forward_call\": \"Replicate the OM proteome (already planned by the data provider for summer 2026). Characterize the Caulobacter SigU regulon via SigU-induction RNA-seq (ectopic vanillate-inducible SigU expression) followed by genome-wide DE.\",\n13\t    \"data_source\": \"Substory conclusions: S1 (C-slot) + S2 (C-slot) + S3 (C-slot) + S4 (C-slot) + S5 (C-slot); narrative/00_throughline.md; REPORT.md \\u00a7Future directions\"\n14\t  },\n15\t  \"speaker_notes\": \"The OM proteome replication is the immediate near-term experiment \\u2014 the data provider already has it slated for summer 2026, and it nails down the two post-hoc findings (lptC2 transcript-protein decoupling and Pal-Tol induction) before publication. The SigU regulon characterization is the longer novel arc: no Caulobacter SigU regulon exists in the literature, and the late ChvI cohort from NB03 gives us a ready candidate target list to validate.\\n\\n**Sources:** Substory conclusions: S1 (C-slot) + S2 (C-slot) + S3 (C-slot) + S4 (C-slot) + S5 (C-slot); narrative/00_throughline.md; REPORT.md \\u00a7Future directions\",\n16\t  \"id\": 30,\n17\t  \"position\": 31\n18\t}\n19\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24e07efb-61d3-4a78-9f0b-69fa16f28734","uuid":"d17cf5c8-1ef6-4f1d-82af-c36b6817c118","timestamp":"2026-06-07T04:22:16.071Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/CO001.slide.json","content":"{\n  \"layout\": \"deck_close\",\n  \"content\": {\n    \"unified_point\": \"A single envelope catastrophe \\u2014 lipid A loss \\u2014 triggers five partially independent adaptive layers (Fur-released transport, ChvI two-phase signaling, constitutive sphingolipid substitution, peptidoglycan remodeling, and cross-species structural unavailability) that together explain how and why Caulobacter alone tolerates the deletion.\",\n    \"key_takeaways\": [\n      \"Fur-released transport relief is real and fitness-bearing in Path A transporters, but the SspB-buffered respiratory arm shows no fitness signal.\",\n      \"ChvI drives a two-phase program \\u2014 regulators early, envelope-structural genes late \\u2014 but the membrane substitute itself is set elsewhere.\",\n      \"A constitutive anionic-sphingolipid pool substitutes for lipid A, transported by maintained Lpt machinery \\u2014 not an inducible emergency response.\",\n      \"Peptidoglycan synthesis is broadly downshifted with targeted Pal-Tol induction \\u2014 a coordinated remodel that raises why only Caulobacter survives it.\",\n      \"The sphingolipid pathway and ChvG-ChvI are taxonomically restricted; comparator species lack the route entirely and use alternative strategies instead.\"\n    ],\n    \"forward_call\": \"Replicate the OM proteome (already planned by the data provider for summer 2026). Characterize the Caulobacter SigU regulon via SigU-induction RNA-seq (ectopic vanillate-inducible SigU expression) followed by genome-wide DE.\",\n    \"data_source\": \"Substory conclusions: S1 (C-slot) + S2 (C-slot) + S3 (C-slot) + S4 (C-slot) + S5 (C-slot); narrative/00_throughline.md; REPORT.md \\u00a7Future directions\"\n  },\n  \"speaker_notes\": \"The OM proteome replication is the immediate near-term experiment \\u2014 the data provider already has it slated for summer 2026, and it nails down the two post-hoc findings (lptC2 transcript-protein decoupling and Pal-Tol induction) before publication. The SigU regulon characterization is the longer novel arc: no Caulobacter SigU regulon exists in the literature, and the late ChvI cohort from NB03 gives us a ready candidate target list to validate.\\n\\n**Sources:** Substory conclusions: S1 (C-slot) + S2 (C-slot) + S3 (C-slot) + S4 (C-slot) + S5 (C-slot); narrative/00_throughline.md; REPORT.md \\u00a7Future directions\",\n  \"id\": 30,\n  \"position\": 31\n}\n","numLines":19,"startLine":1,"totalLines":19}}}
